rry\n      ôñ sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-",
      "cs\nimport Aesop\n\nset_option aesop.check.all true\n\n@[ext]\nstructure MyProd (öÝ öý : Type _) where\n  fst : öÝ\n  snd : öý\n\nvariable {öÝ öý ö° öÇ ö¿: Type}\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    ôñ sorry\n    ôñ sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd öÝ öý} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n\n/--\ninfo: Try this:\n\n  [apply]     ext : 1\n    ôñ sorry\n    ôñ ext : 1\n      ôñ sorry\n      ôñ sorry\n---\nwarning: declaration uses 'sorry'\n-/\n#guard_msgs in\nexample {p q : MyProd öÝ (MyProd öý ö°)} : p = q := by\n  aesop? (add safe Aesop.BuiltinRules.ext)\n    (config := { warnOnNonterminal := false })\n  all_goals sorry\n```\n\nThe problem asks us to replace the `sorry` at the end of the second example. The `sorry` is in the `all_goals` part of the proof.\n\nLet's analyze what happens when we use `aesop?` with the `ext` rule:\n\n1. The first `ext` (at line 10) is applied. This is for `p = q` where `p, q : MyProd öÝ (MyProd öý ö°)`.\n2. This creates two goals:\n   - `p.fst = q.fst`\n   - `p.snd = q.snd`\n3. The `all_goals sorry` attempts to solve both goals with `sorry`.\n4. The first goal `p.fst = q.fst` is solved by `sorry`.\n5. The second goal `p.snd = q.snd` is where the second `ext` (at line 13) is applied.\n6. This creates two more goals:\n   - `p.snd.fst = q.snd.fst`\n   - `p.snd.snd = q.snd.snd`\n7. The `all_goals sorry` (line 14) is intended to solve these two subgoals.\n8. The `sorry` on line 16 is the one that needs to be replaced. This `sorry` is meant to solve the goal `p.snd.snd = q.snd.snd`.\n\nTo fix the proof, we need to replace the final `sorry` with a valid proof term. In this case, the goal is an equality of `ö°` terms. If `p.snd.snd` and `q.snd.snd` are both `ö°`, then `rfl` should work if they are definitionally equal, or we might need more context.\n\nLooking at the problem, t